Extending the autocomplete attribute

This is an effort to analyze the structures of address forms in a somewhat machine readable way.

This work is based on the following assumptions:

  • The autocomplete spec was written with the intent to find a lowest common denominator that should work for all countries. An analysis of real-world web-forms indicates that those forms cannot be properly annotated with today's autocomplete attribute because it lacks expressiveness. Probably many site owners don't have a choice because shipping companies or local customs tell them how an address form should look like.
  • There are certain aspects that just apply to a few countries (e.g. Japan has phonetic names, Spain has paternal and maternal last names, Hungary splits the name of a street from the type of a street). The fact that these concepts only apply to a few countries does not make them go away. We should allow storing a few extra fields for Japanese, Spanish, Hungarian, ... addresses (i.e. decide which fields to offer based on the country of an address) because oftentimes customers and merchants are in the same country and share the same cultural norms when it comes to address forms.
  • I don't think that we can immediately fix autofill for all countries and this analysis does not cover all countries. I hope that this document leads to an architecture that can be extended.
  • We may need to combine certain atomic pieces of information into a single field (e.g. a house number and an apartment number). This process is probably very locale specific and needs to grow over time. The fact that we don't know how to combine two fields into one fillable string for some countries yet, hopefully does not invalidate the overall idea.

Note that this is work in progress. Feedback is highly appreciated.

-Dominic Battré (battre at google . com)

Big and global questions

  • Do we want to support multiple field concurrent types? E.g. I see "name or company" fields. I don't see an obvious syntax for adding this capability to the autocomplee attribute. If you search for '[' below you can find examples where a website requested one (or more) of multiple field types.
  • How do we model the "everything else" field type? Do we want to call it "address-overflow", "address-supplement" (this seems to be a term that is quite common in many countries), "building-and-location-in-building" (also common)? The latter may be too narrow because it does not cover a company name or c/o. Some websites would not want a company or c/o in their "everything else" fileds while others would want them.
    Instead of an "everything else" type we could ask websites to enumerate what should go into the list (see the previous bullet point).
  • Are we ok with introducing country specific concepts? E.g. Hungary separates the name of a street (e.g. "Amphitheatre") from the type of the street ("Ave", "Pkwy", "Blvd", ...). I haven't seen this anywhere else. It's essential to fill Hungarian address forms but we should not offer this to all users.
  • Do we allow forms to specify an encoding? E.g. Japanese forms are picky about ASCII, full-width or half-width characters.
  • TODO: The patronymic name is based on the first name of the father. As per Eastern Slavic naming customs, it is written in these countries in all legal and identity documents. Countries mentioned there include Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, and to an extent in Kyrgyzstan, Georgia. But the list of affected countries is longer.
  • Many naming questions...
    • How do we call the location information to find a place inside a building? "location-in-building"? "sub-building"?
    • How do we name things that are very country/culture specific (Hungary's separation between street name and street type, entrecalles, ...)?

# AR - Argentina üá¶üá∑

Argentinian address forms rely on street names, house numbers, floors (Piso) and apartments (Departamento). Floors and apartments can be requested in a single input field or in two separate fields.

On the street address level, we frequently see between streets, i.e. a field in which one specifies the names of two crossing streets to help locate the house number.

The forms ask for states/provinces and localities/cities.

Oftentimes the address form was filled via an address search box.

Frequently a DNI was requested (national identification number).

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:
  • street-name (calle)
  • house-number (n√∫mero)
  • floor (piso)
  • apartment (departamento)
  • floor and/or apartment (piso y/o departamento)
  • "between streets" (entrecalles) - either with one input field or with two
  • additional information (datos adicionales/aclaraci√≥n adicional/observations/Direcci√≥n Complementaria

Open questions

  • How do we deal with address-overflow? Oftentimes, this seems to ask for information within a building - floor and apartment - but theoretically it could be more flexible. Do we want to rely on "location-in-building"?
  • Do we want to support entrecalles (between streets) which are split across two fields? - Do we want to combine this with "landmark"?
  • Two forms asked for a "Lote" - a piece of land (a lot / parcel of land).
  • One form asked for a "Torre", which literally means a tower but in this context it would refer to a part of a building (e.g. front-building, a wing of a building, ...).
  • The concept of "partido" is not fully clear to me. One form asked for (provincia, partido, localidad), which I see as (province, part of a city, city). Another form asked for (partido, provincia) but no city. Maybe this was implied by the zip code?

# AU - Australia üá¶üá∫

Australia has largely simple addresses with
  • address lines 1, 2, 3, or
  • street name, house number and up to one field for extra information (apartment number, floor, etc.).

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:
  • street-name
  • house-number (also referred to as street no)
  • location-in-building / building-and-location-in-building (Lvl, Apt or Unit No.; Building/Floor/Apartment/Unit; Suite, building, level, etc. (optional)

Open questions

  • none?

# BR - Brazil üáßüá∑

Brazil relies heavily on structured addresses. Basically every form has separate fields for street name, house number and often an complement (for apartments, blocks, ...). Oftentimes, a lot of information is derived from the CEP (postal code).

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:
  • street-name (endere√ßo)
  • house-number (n√∫mero)

The capital city of Brasilia is divided into sectors. The sectors appear as abbreviations in the address (three to four capital letters). A sector is divided into quadras, which are themselves divided into blocks (source).

While most cities seem to follow a "street name, house number" schema, the capital Brasilia uses "sector, quadra, block, floor", e.g. SBN ‚Äì Quadra 13 ‚Äì Bloco B ‚Äì 8¬∫ andar. Here is an image of "Superquadra Sul (sector) 303 (quadra)", where each building is called a block. The address refers to block B and floor number 8.

I looked up a zip code in Brasilia (70670-503) and a website (casasbahia.com.br) translated this into a two-line Endere√ßo: 

CLSW 101 Bloco Cn
Setor Sudoeste - Bras√≠lia - DF

It is pretty common that the website only asks for the zip code (CEP), derives the Endere√ßo, and then asks the user to enter N√∫mero (house number). For an address in Brasilia, I suppose that you would specify "s/n" as the number (as you don't have one - s/n = "sem n√∫mero" = without number; some websites have a checkbox for this).

For these reasons, I am not sure whether Bloco in a Complemento field refers to a block in Brasilia or needs to be supported as a separate field type.

# DE - Germany üá©üá™

German sites often ask for street name and house number in a single designated filed or two separate fields. This is often complemented by an address extension ("Addresszusatz"), a catch all field that can list an apartment number (rare), c/o person or a company name.

German address forms are special in that they often ask for gender, saluation, and social / academic titles.

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:

  • street-name (Stra√üe)
  • house-number (Hausnummer)
  • address extension (Addresszusatz) - This can contain an apartment, company, c/o.
  • salutation (Herr/Frau - Mr./Mrs.)
  • academic title (Titel)

Open questions

  • Should we distinguish the salutation from an academic or noble title?
  • How do we model the address-supplement field?

# FR - France üá´üá∑

French websites often work well with an address-line1 and 2. The websites may specify what to put into each line but it looks like address-line1 always gets the street name and house number.

Some websites ask for a street name and house number and then also have overflow fields.

Many websites asked for a (binary) gender.

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:
  • street name (Num√©ro)
  • house number (Voie)
  • building (B√¢timent)
  • floor (√âtage)
  • stair case (Escalier) - just once in the sample
  • door (Porte) - just once in the sample
  • academic title (Titel)

Open questions

  • Do we want to use lieu-dit for address-level3? Some cities have multiple sub-cities. A lieu-dit is the name of a subdivision of the city, usually very small (2-3 houses). Typically you would would put the lieu-dit into the street-address/address-lineX field because you don‚Äôt have street/house numbers in a lieu-dit.
  • Do we want to support door codes?

# GB - Great Britain üá¨üáß

British houses have either numbers or names, or even both. As per this, a full address should contain a premise identifier, street details, post town and the postcode. The premise identifier requires at least one of the 4 premise elements: Company name, Building number, Building name, Sub building name.

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:

  • street name
  • house number
  • house name
  • town (separate field from a city - probably referring to a postal town). Occurred once in the sample set.
  • overflow field
Street name + house number/name are often combined with another overflow field.

Open questions

  • This requires some checking with a British resident. My proposals are too much guess work.
  • Do we want to distinguish between postal town and city?
This is an entertaining article on the oddities of UK addresses.

Feedback from a native Hungarian:

"K√∂zter√ºlet jellege" is a "street type", such as {street, road, drive, avenue, boulevard, square, etc.}. While in most languages the street name emcompasses the name and the street type, in Hungarian they are often separated in official records. "K√∂zter√ºlet neve" could be "Amphitheatre", "K√∂zter√ºlet jellege" could be "Pkwy".

"√âp√ºlet" (Building): is only used when multiple buildings share the same house number, so it identifies which one. Can be another number or letter.

"L√©pcs≈ëh√°z" (Staircase): serves a similar purpose as "√âp√ºlet" (Building) when there are multiple entrances to a single building, and there are mailboxes next to each.

"Emelet" (Floor) / "Ajt√≥" (Door): These are a more structured way to refer to an "apartment number", "flat number", or "room number" in an office. These historically have the structure of "floor / door", e.g. "3/1", meaning 3rd floor, 1st apartment within that floor. The "door number" is most often a locally unique identifier within the floor, not within the building as common in the US.

# ID - Indonesia üáÆüá©

Indonesian addresses are special because of their depth, using all of address-level1 through address-level4. Sometimes the higher address levels (3 and 4) need to be entered into a textarea along with the street address or into address-lineX fields. The address-levels are:

  • address-level1: Provinsi (Province)
  • address-level2: Kota (City)
  • address-level3: Kecamatan (District, part of a city or regency)
  • address-level4: Kelurahan (Subdistrict, part of a district)
Indonesian addresses often rely on <select> elements. The values of one <select> element may only be populated after the user filled the previous one. Sites also ship their own custom <select> elements.

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:

  • One form had an address line 4

# IN - India üáÆüá≥

Indian addresses forms have surprising naming conventions. Forms commonly ask for a 'House no/Apartment name'. The 'house number' is an apartment number (not the sequence of a house in a street) and the apartment name is the name of a building (most buildings have a name; this is not referring to the name of an apartment).

Another important aspect that is not common in other countries is a 'locality' (sometimes referred to as 'area details'). An example would be 'HITEC City' in Hyderabad. It's a name for an area that people know and use for orientation. Another example would be 'old town'.

A 'Colony' is a named group of buildings that belong to each other, e.g. sharing amenities. Also serves as a landmark.

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:

  • landmark
  • building (apartment name)
  • apartment (house no)
  • street name

Open questions

  • Should we support towers?

Progress: ‚òë First round of cleanup, ‚òë Discussed with a (former) resident - but India is large and there could be multiple different conventions.

# MX - Mexico üá≤üáΩ

Every address form asks for a colonia, which is a neighborhood in a Mexican city (which has no jurisdictional autonomy or representation) or a gated community. It is interesting that some cities have a municipality, but not all. This probably means that we treat a colonia as an address-level4 to have a fixed assignment. If there is no address-level3 fields, we probaby want to combine it with the city field (address-level2). Alternatively, we would need to be able to split a city into the city and delegacion. This is one of the cases where I don't know how ot read the autocomplete spec.

Missing field types

The following cases are currently missing in the autocomplete spec and occurred on multiple sites:

  • street-name
  • external number (house number)
  • internal number (apartment number)
  • entre calles (between streets) or landmark
  • Colonia and sometimes Delegaci√≥n o Municipio (Delegation or Municipality)

Open questions

  • How to deal with address-level3 or address-level4 for colonia (see above)

# NG - Nigeria üá≥üá¨

Practically all websites I have seen relied on unstructured addresses. I observed that most websites I saw were hosted via WooCommerce which may be a common practice or a sampling bias. I saw a single exceptional website which asked for the LGA (Local Government Area). As per official guidelines, addresses have the following order of elements (see page 28 of here): District, Postcode, City, Local Government Area, State, Country. This means that a city would need to be address-level3. In practice my sample of sites did not ask for LGAs frequently (except for one page) so there would be a high chance of confusion if we supported this field as address-level2.

  • delivery-instructions

  • How to deal with LGA (see above)?

# RU - Russia üá∑üá∫

Russian addresses are super confusing:

This source points out that address data can be transliterated and translated. It contains some common terms. The following quote helps understanding the structures. ("n.b." are by myself, I am not 100% sure these are correct)

"The Russian address system might get a bit confusing, as each address is often made up of a bunch of information, an inheritance of the Soviet mass construction of tall multi-apartment buildings. So, you‚Äôll usually have a ‚Äúdom‚Äù [n.b.: –¥–æ–º] number, which refers to the whole complex; then, since many housing complexes in Russia are massive and contain multiple buildings, most of which are accessible from an inner courtyard, you‚Äôll also have a ‚Äúkorpus‚Äù [n.b.: –∫–æ—Ä–ø.] number referring to the specific building; the ‚Äústroenie‚Äù [n.b.: —Å—Ç—Ä.] number is quite similar to the ‚Äúkorpus‚Äù, as it still refers to the specific building of a complex having a common entrance from the main street; then, you may have a ‚Äúpod‚Äôezd‚Äù [n.b.: –ü–æ–¥—ä–µ–∑–¥], aka the actual entrance to an apartment located in a multi-storey building; and finally, the ‚Äúkvartira‚Äù [n.b.: –ö–≤–∞—Ä—Ç–∏—Ä–∞], referring to the specific apartment accessible from the specific ‚Äúpod‚Äôezd‚Äù, inside the specific ‚Äústroenie‚Äù or ‚Äúkorpus‚Äù of a certain ‚Äúdom‚Äù." - https://thetranssiberians.com/2015/08/30/hostels-in-russia/
A Russian colleague clarified this as follows:
Stroenie is a building inside a building set that are not accessible from a street. Good example - buildings on a factory territory. Korpus is a building inside a building set with its own entrance from a street. Usually you can have one of them. The interesting thing begins when a territory is divided into several. In that case a building may receive ‚Äúkorpus‚Äù. Example: Moscow, Ulitsa Rogova, 12 korpus 2 stroenie 1. Many government documents have just one field ‚Äúkorpus/stroenie‚Äù. Then you will fill in with ‚Äúk.2 s.1‚Äù.
Finally, this is handy because it contains a number of abbreviation and translations.
